        },
        {
          "name": "Write Concurrency",
          "value": "Multi-writer via 64-stripe partitioned locks (PR #247). FNV-1a hash of first 9 bytes routes to partition. Writers to different classification-chain partitions proceed concurrently. 5 partitioned_lock tests + 6 partitioned_tx tests",
          "target": "Multi-writer",
          "met": true,
          "source": "PR #247. PartitionedLockManager: 64 stripes (power of 2 for fast modulo). Key routing: FNV-1a hash of prefix byte + classification chain hash → partition. Per-partition Mutex<()> locks. Deadlock-free multi-partition acquisition via sorted lock ordering. Inspired by Silo (Tu et al., SOSP 2013).",
          "comparisons": [
            { "system": "SQLite", "value": "Single-writer (WAL)", "source": "Global write lock" },
            { "system": "RocksDB", "value": "Concurrent writers (column families)", "source": "Lock-free memtable + WAL serialization" },
            { "system": "Neo4j", "value": "Concurrent writers (record-level)", "source": "Enterprise only" },
            { "system": "Silo (SOSP 2013)", "value": "Epoch-based partitioned validation", "source": "Academic reference for partitioned concurrency" }
          ]
        },
        {
          "name": "Write-Set Conflict Detection",
          "value": "Cross-partition tracking — transactions spanning multiple partitions detected and resolved",
          "target": "Conflict detection",
          "met": true,
          "source": "PR #247. ConflictGraph tracks write sets per transaction. Cross-partition writes acquire locks in sorted order (deadlock-free). Conflict detection at commit time — overlapping write sets abort the later transaction. 5 conflict_graph tests.",
          "comparisons": [
            { "system": "RocksDB", "value": "OptimisticTransactionDB (OCC)", "source": "Write conflict detection at commit" },
            { "system": "CockroachDB", "value": "Write intent tracking", "source": "Per-range lock tables" },
            { "system": "TiKV", "value": "Percolator-style 2PC", "source": "Distributed transaction protocol" }
          ]
        },
        {
          "name": "Isolation Level",
          "value": "Serializable (SSI) — strongest isolation level",
          "target": "Serializable",
          "met": true,
          "comparisons": [
            { "system": "SQLite", "value": "Serializable" },
            { "system": "RocksDB", "value": "Snapshot Isolation" },
            { "system": "Neo4j", "value": "Read Committed" },
            { "system": "PostgreSQL", "value": "Serializable (optional, significant overhead)" }
          ]
        },
        {
          "name": "Epoch-Based Reclamation",
          "value": "EpochGuard + EpochTable — safe memory reclamation for concurrent readers. 8 tests",
          "target": "Built",
          "met": true,
          "source": "EpochGuard protects concurrent readers from seeing freed memory. EpochTable tracks active epochs for safe reclamation. 5 epoch_guard + 3 epoch_table tests.",
          "comparisons": [
            { "system": "RocksDB", "value": "Reference counting", "source": "SuperVersion reference counting" },
            { "system": "Sled", "value": "Epoch-based reclamation (crossbeam-epoch)", "source": "Similar approach" }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "narrative": "Concurrency has been completely transformed from a known gap (5.5, single-writer) to a strong capability (8.0, multi-writer) via PR #247. The 64-stripe partitioned lock design, inspired by Silo (Tu et al., SOSP 2013), routes keys to partitions using FNV-1a hash of the first 9 bytes (prefix byte + classification chain hash). Writers to different classification-chain partitions proceed fully concurrently — this is governance-aware partitioning, not random sharding. Reads remain lock-free via CoW snapshots (unchanged). Cross-partition conflict detection tracks write sets per transaction and resolves conflicts at commit time, with deadlock-free multi-partition acquisition via sorted lock ordering. The key insight: classification chains naturally partition data by governance domain (e.g., Alberta wells vs BC wells), so most concurrent writes hit different partitions. Epoch-based reclamation (EpochGuard + EpochTable) ensures safe memory management for concurrent readers. 27 tests across concurrency and transaction modules. Remaining work: benchmark multi-writer throughput under realistic contention patterns and tune partition count for different deployment sizes.",
